title: For Sale:  12 ga tactical shotgun
postcontent:
I have a brand new, never fired, IAC (Interstate Arms) Hawk 982 12 gauge tactical shotgun. Includes the shotgun, box, and owners manual.

A little background on this gun:
For those of you who may not be aware, the patent on the Remington 870 tactical shotgun (standard issue for most police and SWAT teams), expired a # of years back.  Since then, it has been completely legal for companies to reproduce the 870, under their own name of course. This is exactly what this shotgun is, a Remington 870 clone. It looks, feels, and operates like a Remington 870, only it is a third of the cost. All 870 accessories, add-ons, and upgrades will work with this shotgun as well, with one exception, the barrel. The barrel on the IAC model uses a little bit thicker steel. There are plenty of reviews and videos about this model on youtube, check them out. You'll see, for the money, these are one of the best home defense/tactical shotguns out there. 

I have owned one of these exact shotguns for years, and I absolutely love it. Very dependable and rugged. Shoots both 2.75" and 3" shells. A friend of mine recently wanted me to purchase one online for him since he liked mine so much. So I did, and he ran into some financial issues and is not able to take it, so it is up for sale. I paid $200 plus shipping plus a $50 FFL transfer fee. I'm selling it at a loss for $225. I may consider trades, but they would be at a higher value ($250+) depending on the trade.

Here are the specs for this shotgun from IAC:
12 gauge
18.5" barrel
3" chamber
5 round capacity (can add the 870 hi-capacity tube for 2 or 3 more rounds if desired)
Polymer stock
Matte black finish
Machined, solid steel receiver
Adjustable ghost ring sights
38.5" overall length
7 pounds 

Must be 18 yrs old with a valid OH ID to purchase. No shipping, FTF only. Willing to meet in the greater Akron area. CCW preferred.

title: For Sale:  Tactical shotgun (12ga)
postcontent:
I have a brand new, never fired, IAC (Interstate Arms) Hawk 982 12 gauge tactical shotgun. Includes the shotgun, box, and owners manual.

A little background on this gun:
For those of you who may not be aware, the patent on the Remington 870 tactical shotgun (standard issue for most police and SWAT teams), expired a # of years back.  Since then, it has been completely legal for companies to reproduce the 870, under their own name of course. This is exactly what this shotgun is, a Remington 870 clone. It looks, feels, and operates like a Remington 870, only it is a third of the cost. All 870 accessories, add-ons, and upgrades will work with this shotgun as well, with one exception, the barrel. The barrel on the IAC model uses a little bit thicker steel. There are plenty of reviews and videos about this model on youtube, check them out. You'll see, for the money, these are one of the best home defense/tactical shotguns out there. 

I have owned one of these exact shotguns for years, and I absolutely love it. Very dependable and rugged. Shoots both 2.75" and 3" shells. A friend of mine recently wanted me to purchase one online for him since he liked mine so much. So I did, and he ran into some financial issues and is not able to take it, so it is up for sale. I paid $200 plus shipping plus a $50 FFL transfer fee. I'm selling it at a loss for $225. I may consider trades, but they would be at a higher value ($250+) depending on the trade.

Here are the specs for this shotgun from IAC:
12 gauge
18.5" barrel
3" chamber
5 round capacity (can add the 870 hi-capacity tube for 2 or 3 more rounds if desired)
Polymer stock
Matte black finish
Machined, solid steel receiver
Adjustable ghost ring sights
38.5" overall length
7 pounds 

Must be 18 yrs old with a valid OH ID to purchase. No shipping, FTF only. Willing to meet in the greater Akron area. CCW preferred.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Glock 35 .40 w/ Lone Wolf 9mm Conversion Barrel
postcontent:
Up for sale/trade is my Glock 35 .40 w/ Lone Wolf 9mm Conversion Barrel. The .40 barrel has just under 300rds and the 9mm barrel has 100rds through it. The Lone Wolf conversion barrel is precision machined and is considered to be much more accurate than the factory Glock barrel. Gun comes with 1 Glock Factory 15rd .40 magazine, 1 Glock Factory 17rd 9mm magazine, and 1 Korean 33rd 9mm magazine. Gun comes stock, but a Grip Force Beaver-tail has been added to maintain a higher grip and prevent slide bite. For those of you who are unaware, the Glock 35 is the "competition" version of the Glock 22. The G35 features: Extended Slide Release lever, Extended magazine release, 4.5lb trigger, and a longer sight radius that it's G22 counterpart. This gun is used by many competition shooters and it's rock solid reliable and it is in perfect condition with no slide wear or scratches. The only reason I'm getting rid of it is because I recently bought a Glock 30 for carry and see no other point for .40 for me. I carried this gun for self-defense the past year with the .40 barrel for the stopping power and used the 9mm barrel for much cheaper training with the same platform. The only thing needed to convert the gun from .40 to 9mm is to remove the slide, like you would for routine cleaning, remove the .40 barrel, and insert the 9mm barrel using the same guide rod and everything. Load up the 9mm magazine and have fun! This gun sells new for ~$650 online and even higher at most retail shops. I paid ~$120 for the conversion barrel and the gun also comes with the grip force adapter and 2 Factory magazines. title: For Trade:  FT: Home Bar/Man Cave Upgrade - ISO: Shotgun or Rifle
location: North-east Fort Wayne, Fort Wayne, Indiana
postcontent:
I'm looking for a dependable home defense weapon (shotgun, smooth-bore preferably) in trade for everything. I'm not "shooting for the moon" (forgive the pun), and I'm open to any offer you'd like to make, but for now I'm not taking cash offers for individual pieces or interested in other types of trades.

  Up for trade is a home bar / man cave upgrade stuffed with more than enough products to either get your man cave started or fill out your den enough to truly call it the home bar you've always been looking for. These are all display pieces that I've taken (with permission) from my work over the last seven years or so that I don't have a place for in my own home bar right now. Every piece has been treated respectfully... it has first been displayed in a store set, and then spent some time in my own home bar set, so they have some general wear and tear but are in good condition.

  I would like to keep the set together so I will give preference to those trade offers. I don't have a great deal of extra money right now, so any "+cash offers" you make I will likely have to turn down.

  A few important things I'd like to point out are:

 The Camel neon is one of the old models that are built to last - the new neons all have these sh*tty-ass transformers that go out after six months and cost more than the whole damned neon to replace. These old models are built like a brick sh*thouse and as long as you treat it with respect, it should last you as long time. I can send you as pic of the transformer if you want to take a look.

  Some of the signs are vintage (none of them are reproductions), such as the bud tin and the cigar clock. I have no idea on "value" but they add a nice old school elegance... the cigar clock runs on batteries (two AA's), and must be plugged in to light up. It keeps fairly accurate time with fresh batteries and I've never had to replace anything, but I've added more neons to my home bar and don't have room for it anymore. The minute hand is beat up but doesn't impede functionality, and you could replace it easily and cheaply if you wanted to spruce it up.

  If there's anything else you feel you need to fill out your bar, let me know and I can probably dig something up from my collection.

  Another important point to make is that I'm a big guy... I don't take something home that's going to break under me. I can sit in those chairs *comfortably,* so unless you've got me beat by a hundred pounds you can rest easy. Aside from that, you can see everything included... I can text or email you any more pictures that you want. If you live in Fort Wayne, I can deliver it all to you. If you're not, I'll try to find a fair middle ground with you. 

  Let me know if you have any questions and I'll get back with you as soon as possible.

  Thanks for taking a look. I appreciate it!

A. Sorry, I do not do gunsmithing.

Q. Will you ship?
A. Yes - go to www.preciseshooter.com -> How to buy and read the section for buying outside Seattle area. Shipping via insured USPS Priority Mail will be $30.
